latures to grant their sisters the vote, they often approved of that same right being denied to “foreigners” and Indigenous men and women. By situating the suffragists’ struggle in the colonial history of Prairie Canada, this powerful and passionate book shows that the right to vote meant different things to different people – political rights and emancipation for some, domination and democracy denied for others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSuffragezPrairie ProvincesxHistory. 0aSuffragistszPrairie ProvincesxHistory. 0aVotingzPrairie ProvincesxHistory. 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etc.zPrairie ProvincesxHistory. 0aWomenxSuffragezCanadaxHistory. 0aWomenxSuffragezPrairie ProvincesxHistory. 0aWomenzPrairie ProvincesxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / Women .2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311127253508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020z978311127473708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311141765340uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077486189240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774861892423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774861892/original  a978-3-11-127253-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-127473-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-141765-3  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles